  • Management of eye disease:
    • Steroids : oral or IV (preferred if severe inflammation)
    • Teprotumumab - monoclonal antibody. (preferred for proptosis and diplopia)
  • Symptomatic management: Propraonolol for beta blockade.
  • Antithyroid drugs : thionamides: Carbimazole / methimazole and PTU
  • Methimazole is active metabolite of carbimazole; Equivalent dose of carbimazole is 40% higher.
  • Methimazole is 10 times more potent than PTU and is the drug of choice in adults and children. (Katzung)
  • Both carbimazole and PTU inhibit thyroid peroxidase which inhibits iodination of tyrosine residues on thyroglobulin.
    | Also can cause ANCA positive vasculitis. | ANCA positive vasculitis |
    | Slowly absorbed | Rapidly absorbed |
  • Euthyroid status is expected in 4 - 6 weeks. (or 3-8 weeks) because only synthesis of new hormone is blocked and preexisting intrathyroidal hormone stores must be depleted.
  • Carb/methimazole has longer half life.
  • But has slower absorption
  • More inhibition of iodine organification.
  • Both thionamides cross the placental but PTU crosses less because it is more protein bound
  • High intrathyroidal concentrations, outlasting the plasma half life are seen with both thionamide so that plasma half life is irrelavant
  • Thionamides have a high risk of agranulocytosis compared to other drugs that cause it.
  • Agranulocytosis occurs within 2-3 months of start of treatment.
  • If it occurs, treatment with thionamides is contraindicated.

Pharmacologic options for Anticoagulation

  • DOACS are preferred except in the following scenarios
    1. Rheumatic Mitral stenosis causing AF (DOACS had higher morbidity and INVICTUS trial)
    2. Mechanical heart valve prosthesis in situ
    3. DOAC interactions with other drugs
      1. Chronic antiviral therapy can increase DOAC anticoagulant activity.
      2. P-glycoprotein inducers can increase DOAC efflux from guy and reduce anticoagulant activity
  • The side effect is idiosyncratic. It can happen at any time. No point in monitoring for it!
  • Ask the patient to come to hospital if symptoms occur. In contrast to drugs like ?clozapine => progressive neutropenia

Heparin induced thrombocytopaenia

  • Antibodies are produced against heparin-platelet factor 4 complexes.
  • This is found on platelets and endothelial cells. Circulating immune complexes bind to platelet (thrombocytopaenia) and blood vessels (endothelial damage) and can result in DIC.

  • Antibodies bind to PF4 on the platelet surface and stimulate platelet activation.

  • This results in thrombocytopaenia (platelets found to to antibodies are removed by the Reticuloendothelial system) - commonest manifestation.

  • Associated ⭐thrombosis (venous more than arterial) - around 50%, if untreated.

    • Manifestations include pulmonary embolism, skin necrosis, limb gangrene.
    • Arterial thrombi (MI, stroke) can also occur.

  • Bleeding is rare!

  • Onset is 5 - 10 days after onset of therapy.

  • Risk with Heparin > risk with LMWH (fractionated heparin)

  • Risk with High dose > risk with low dose

  • "4 T" score is used to assess the likelihood of HIT.

    • Points are assigned based on
    1. Severity of thrombocytopenia
    2. Timing of thrombocytopenia
    3. Presence of Thrombosis of other sequelae
    4. Thrombocytopaenia due to other reasons

  • Treatment: Stop heparin and start non heparin anti-coagulation (like a direct thrombin inhibitor)

#2021GM-JUL/Q25

Strategies are different for mechanical valves and bioprosthetic valves.
Source

  • Depends on the which valve is replaced, which type of mechanical valve is used and presence of other thromboembolic risk factors.
  • All mechanical valves require lifelong anticoagulation with Vitamin K agonist.
  • There is now ❌NO RECOMMENDATION❌ for giving antiplatelets along with VKAs for thromboprophylaxis with mechanical valves.
  • So far, the only option for anticoagulation with mechanical heart valves is warfarin.
  • Target INR is 2.5 for 3 to 6 months if there are no other reasons to anticoagulate using a VKA.
    • This is because the first 90-180 days are considered high risk.
  • All patients (with no other indication for anticoagulation) get aspirin after the period of anticoagulation.

[!TIP] Only indication for intra-venous vitamin K (and PCC) is

  • Life threatening bleeding

#2021BSQ-NOV/Q36

'Special' in SVE means 'innervation of branchial arch derived muscles'

  • SVE: Motor efferents to facial muscles
    • and Posterior auricular nerve and branch to posterior belly of digastric and stylohyoid muscle, facial expression, stapedius muscle
  • GVE: Parasympathetic efferents lacrimal glands, submandibular glands and sublingual glands (but not the parotid gland (that's by glossopharyngeal nerve) - via the greater petrosal nerve and chorda tympani
  • SVA: Afferent taste fibers from front 2/3 of the tongue - via the chorda tympani
  • GSA:*Somatic afferents from the pinna and external auditory canal.
  • Bell's palsy is defined as 'idiopathic' isolated facial nerve palsy but a viral (HSV) aetiology is suspected.
    • There is swelling with oedema and inflammatory infiltrate. Damage is greatest in the narrowest part of the passage: the labyrinthine part.
  • But there is a x3 risk during T3 of #pregnancy and week 1 post partum.
    Basis: swelling of the nerve within the confined petrosal canal due to viral infection or reactivation. (HSV)
  • Symptoms: facial nerve weakness occurring over 1 - 2 days. Hyperacusis, loss of taste of anterior 2/3 of tongue, pain behind the ear, ipsilateral decreased tearing or salivation. There will be no other systemic signs (eg no rashes or fever).
  • Maximum weakness is reached within 3 weeks and then improves. Some improvement is always seen within 4 months of onset
  • During recovery "crocodile tears" syndrome can occur. AKA "Gusto-lacrimal" reflex. Patients produce tears when eating or drinking.
    • Crocodiles are said to weep after killing their prey. Source
    • Mechanism uncertain; may be due to regenerative fiber or aberrant synapse formation innervating the lacrimal gland.
  • HIV seroconversion is the most common cause in africa. (because it causes mononeuropathies)
  • Glucocorticoids within 3 day of onset shortens symptom duration.
  • Antivirals are given (specially if weakness if severe) but there is no proven benefit.
  • Synkinesia occurs in 15%. (Involuntary contraction of some facial muscles during voluntary movement of other facial muscles) (can be treated with botulinum toxin)
  • There is a 7% recurrence risk.
